<subSubSection id="11E3DCD4FFBAFFD6FCEEFEB1FAF6FE55" pageId="5" pageNumber="274" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="59468F5FFFBAFFD6FCEEFEB1FAF6FE55" blockId="5.[801,1452,279,463]" pageId="5" pageNumber="274">
<emphasis id="6B8D534DFFBAFFD6FCEEFEB1FA52FEB5" box="[839,1426,279,303]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="274">
Distribution and ecology. – 
<taxonomicName id="9EF9F4DCFFBAFFD6FBC1FEB1FA52FEB5" authorityName="Buerki, Callm., Munzinger &amp; Lowry" authorityYear="2020" baseAuthorityName="Buerki, Callm., Munzinger &amp; Lowry" baseAuthorityYear="2020" box="[1128,1426,279,303]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Sapindaceae" genus="Lepidocupania" kingdom="Plantae" order="Sapindales" pageId="5" pageNumber="274" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="brackenridgei">Lepidocupania brackenridgei</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
is widespread in the 
<collectingCountry id="21EECFCFFFBAFFD6FC4CFE91FB59FED5" box="[997,1177,311,335]" name="Solomon Islands" pageId="5" pageNumber="274">Solomon Islands</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry id="21EECFCFFFBAFFD6FB0DFE91FB3EFED4" box="[1188,1278,311,334]" name="Vanuatu" pageId="5" pageNumber="274">Vanuatu</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry id="21EECFCFFFBAFFD6FAA0FE91FAEFFED5" box="[1289,1327,311,335]" name="Fiji" pageId="5" pageNumber="274">Fiji</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry id="21EECFCFFFBAFFD6FA90FE91FCB0FEF4" name="Wallis and Futuna" pageId="5" pageNumber="274">Wallis and Futuna</collectingCountry>
(Horn Islands), 
<collectingCountry id="21EECFCFFFBAFFD6FB82FEF1FBB1FEF5" box="[1067,1137,343,367]" name="Tonga" pageId="5" pageNumber="274">Tonga</collectingCountry>
and 
<collectingCountry id="21EECFCFFFBAFFD6FB03FEF1FB36FEF5" box="[1194,1270,343,367]" name="Samoa" pageId="5" pageNumber="274">Samoa</collectingCountry>
, where it occurs from sea level to 
<quantity id="9E0122BAFFBAFFD6FC7BFED1FBDFFE14" box="[978,1055,375,399]" metricMagnitude="3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.05" pageId="5" pageNumber="274" unit="m" value="1050.0">1050 m</quantity>
(
<bibRefCitation id="3D68F2AEFFBAFFD6FB87FED1FB7DFE15" author="ADEMA, F." box="[1070,1213,375,399]" pageId="5" pageNumber="274" refId="ref11451" refString="ADEMA, F. (1991). Cupaniopsis Radlk. (Sapindaceae): a monograph. Leiden Bot. Ser. 15." type="book" year="1991">ADEMA, 1991</bibRefCitation>
). This common species occurs in primary and secondary rainforest, but is also found in savannah; it grows on limestone and lava fields.
</paragraph>
